  "doc_id": "57080",
  "text": "Tetraspanins comprise a large family of four-pass transmembrane proteins arising evolutionarily in protists [CITATION_1] . In early unicellular eukaryotes, tetraspanins are believed to play a role in the dynamic regulation of membrane morphology, an activity thought to be subsequently co-opted for cell-cell interactions. As a result, there is an evolutionary link between the emergence of tetraspanins and the development of multicellularity [CITATION_2] . The development of specialized cell-cell interactions and new cell types likely selected for the duplication and differentiation of tetraspanins that evolved to effect specific functions. Thus, primitive fungi have a single tetraspanin, while the size of the tetraspanin family has grown to ten representatives in the sea urchin Strongylocentrotus purpuratus, 17 in the tunicate Ciona intestinalis, and 33 in Homo sapiens [CITATION_3] .",
